    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-02-09T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-02-09T08:00:00-05:00" n="466"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d466">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">251.11 Insull, Samuel/326: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-09T15:00:00+02:00"
                            >February 9, 1934—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 9—12:31 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>14. Your 9, February 3, 3 [<hi rend="italic">1</hi>] p.m. For your information,
                    the latest medical report is now in the Premier’s hands, who told me last <pb
                        facs="0668" n="568" xml:id="pg_568"/> night that it presented a very
                    difficult problem as it says Insull can travel but strong emotion may be fatal.
                    What are your instructions in case the Greek Government asks for an extension or
                    the issuance of a new passport after February 11th?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
